1
00:00:00,140 --> 00:00:02,080
Hi, Austin.

2
00:00:02,080 --> 00:00:03,400
Hi, how are you?

3
00:00:03,400 --> 00:00:03,740
Good.

4
00:00:03,740 --> 00:00:06,080
So, how was the meeting yesterday?

5
00:00:06,080 --> 00:00:24,560
This is part of Designing Open Democracy, and I'm curious to see your take on, like, meeting Herbidus Hopchock, who helped us a few years ago in presenting about his political efforts in building a better democracy.

6
00:00:24,560 --> 00:00:27,320
So, how do you say this guy's name again?

7
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:29,460
I'm pretty sure I mispronounced it.

8
00:00:29,800 --> 00:00:33,500
I've described it as Herbidus Hopchock.

9
00:00:33,500 --> 00:00:36,260
Yeah, but the last name I can't pronounce.

10
00:00:36,260 --> 00:00:39,360
And he's from the, it was the Gilt?

11
00:00:39,360 --> 00:00:41,060
Yeah, Gilt Party, yes.

12
00:00:41,640 --> 00:00:47,780
Of Austria, which tried to do this, which had this thing of open democracy versus liquid democracy.

13
00:00:47,780 --> 00:00:52,020
And I thought, I was quite convinced by a lot of his arguments.

14
00:00:52,020 --> 00:00:54,700
At least I liked the idea of he had a sort of a two-tiered system.

15
00:00:54,780 --> 00:01:00,020
He had, they said, the open group, which anyone could join and vote in.

16
00:01:00,020 --> 00:01:04,099
And then a representative group, which is like a citizen jury selected.

17
00:01:04,099 --> 00:01:07,040
And I thought that was quite a graceful system, right?

18
00:01:07,040 --> 00:01:12,360
And a part of me at first was like, no, well, we need leadership and we need people to sort of lead the discussion.

19
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:15,820
I feel that there's a role for people like that in society.

20
00:01:15,820 --> 00:01:21,360
But that doesn't, maybe that doesn't have to be in the political system itself that happens over here.

21
00:01:21,360 --> 00:01:38,620
There's a public forum debate, the media, et cetera, where we have those discussions, and that filters through to these representative groups, which are literally statistically representative in a mathematical sense, not in a rhetorical ideological sense.

22
00:01:38,620 --> 00:01:52,080
Yeah, I think I remember making an analogy between proportional representation by using the sand analogy, where if you want to show a good mixing, what you need is you can't just take the scoop of sand on the top.

23
00:01:52,280 --> 00:02:04,560
Otherwise, it may just be all blue sand, but instead you need to mix the whole jar together such that when you take a scoop of the top, it can be more accurately representing the whole jar.

24
00:02:04,560 --> 00:02:07,640
So we were talking a bit about statistical representation.

25
00:02:07,640 --> 00:02:09,100
That's...

26
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:10,900
I mean, it works extremely well, right?

27
00:02:10,900 --> 00:02:20,760
Polling is, you know, people love to criticize polls and point out the errors, but, you know, it's very, very rare that polls are wrong by more than 5% or something like that, right?

28
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:24,160
And so when you have, and it's, and, you know, people say, well, 5% is an election.

29
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:25,760
It's like, yeah.

30
00:02:25,760 --> 00:02:31,300
But it also means there's also polling, like there was polling done last year about a basic income, right?

31
00:02:31,300 --> 00:02:38,840
And it came back with sort of, I think it was 60%, 59% support and 20% oppose or something like that, right?

32
00:02:38,840 --> 00:02:52,800
And even with all the margins of error you like built in, that tells us something that changes our perception about whether there was action, you know, about what public perception is, like, that's one of the big things is otherwise we don't know what people think.

33
00:02:53,020 --> 00:03:04,400
If we just sort of lick our thumb and stick it out the window and say, well, you know, my impression is that everyone's really conservative on this point, right?

34
00:03:04,400 --> 00:03:08,180
When you actually ask people, they can surprise you.

35
00:03:08,180 --> 00:03:13,780
Well, glad to see that you quite enjoyed yesterday's catch up with everybody.

36
00:03:13,780 --> 00:03:22,160
Now, I'm really curious as to like, what's your background and what is this new project that you were telling us about yesterday?

37
00:03:22,160 --> 00:03:24,400
Well, my background, how much detail do you want, right?

38
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:29,900
Like, should I start at childhood and go from there or no?

39
00:03:31,140 --> 00:03:35,800
I think they've been more like interested in the like maybe the past few years.

40
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:43,320
And what led you up to creating this new project called the Write In Stone app, if I recall correctly.

41
00:03:43,500 --> 00:03:47,820
Yeah, well, look, I would like to study university if that's okay, right?

42
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:48,920
That might make sense.

43
00:03:48,920 --> 00:03:50,860
When I was in university, that's fine.

44
00:03:50,860 --> 00:03:53,520
Yeah, when I was in university, I was studying philosophy.

45
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:59,900
And I remember the reason I started studying philosophy was I was really impressed on the open day.

46
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:04,820
One of the philosophy lecturers said, I'm the only person who's going to say this to you all day.

47
00:04:04,820 --> 00:04:08,660
Philosophy, the subject that I teach is useless.

48
00:04:08,660 --> 00:04:10,660
It does not have a direct application.

49
00:04:12,120 --> 00:04:15,540
Or it might, but that's not why you do it, right?

50
00:04:15,540 --> 00:04:20,820
You do philosophy because it's removed from direct application, right?

51
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:30,140
That you're not, you're not, it's the place where we say we're not going to game our intellectual system to get a particular result, right?

52
00:04:30,140 --> 00:04:33,360
And it's sort of, you know, I thought that was really interesting.

53
00:04:33,360 --> 00:04:34,880
So and I didn't know what I wanted to do.

54
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:42,960
So that got me involved in philosophy and I was studying that at Macquarie University and the most interesting thing in my degree was going on student exchange.

55
00:04:42,960 --> 00:04:54,540
And I went to Lebanon in 2006 and, you know, I was also doing music and just having a, a real great philosophy college, you know, not too serious kind of time.

56
00:04:54,540 --> 00:05:00,320
And then in 2006, while I was there, I planned to do a full year of student exchange.

57
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:03,980
And then the agreement between the universities dropped out.

58
00:05:03,980 --> 00:05:08,820
So in the second six months of the year, which I'd been planning to stay, I didn't have anything to do.

59
00:05:08,820 --> 00:05:17,200
And I wasn't sure what I wanted to do, but I decided to stay and just keep studying languages and, and, and stay and do a bit of other, you know, stuff outside of university.

60
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:18,900
I was considering maybe a teaching this or something.

61
00:05:18,900 --> 00:05:28,420
And then just as soon, a few days after I would have flown home, but didn't, the war broke out in 2006 with Hezbollah in the south of Israel and the Israelis.

62
00:05:28,420 --> 00:05:31,980
And I was, you know, I woke up hungover, you know.

63
00:05:31,980 --> 00:05:33,340
Oh, what's your background?

64
00:05:33,460 --> 00:05:36,580
Like, like where, where you at?

65
00:05:36,580 --> 00:05:38,020
Where was I at?

66
00:05:38,020 --> 00:05:39,340
I was in, I was in Beirut.

67
00:05:39,340 --> 00:05:48,880
I was in a place called Hamra, which is like, you know, the place where all the foreigners and students and diplomats hang out, you know.

68
00:05:48,880 --> 00:05:56,100
I was studying at the Lebanese American University, and where I was living was between that and this place called the American University of Beirut.

69
00:05:56,100 --> 00:05:58,680
So this is, I mean, I don't want to this place.

70
00:05:58,680 --> 00:06:03,180
It's not just, you know, a tourist trap or anything like that.

71
00:06:03,260 --> 00:06:13,300
This was where all of the, you know, a lot of quite interesting and edgy Arab youth from around the world, from around the Arab region were in Beirut.

72
00:06:13,300 --> 00:06:21,520
So a lot of the people I was hanging out would be like Jordanians or, you know, Emiratis or whatever, who'd come to study in Lebanon, often quite well off, et cetera, et cetera.

73
00:06:21,520 --> 00:06:34,920
But they were connected to the, you know, this was, this is a place of, anyhow, it was an amazing place and I was having a great time experiencing it in a very personal way, not in as, you know, like going there to try and make a career out of it or anything like that.

74
00:06:34,920 --> 00:06:40,480
Then the war broke out and I started writing a blog.

75
00:06:40,480 --> 00:06:46,240
And through people in my network, you got picked up and put to, on the front page of the Canberra Times.

76
00:06:46,240 --> 00:06:55,100
And I thought, well, maybe if I'm getting published on the front page, maybe that means I should consider journalism as a career, which was a terrible idea.

77
00:06:55,100 --> 00:07:01,460
You know, going into journalism in 2006, as people were just being fired from the industry left, right, and center.

78
00:07:01,460 --> 00:07:12,440
But anyhow, you know, like it was, so I spent a lot of time as a journalist, I sort of, I had an agency called Global radio News, and I would do some cable news reporting through them every now and again.

79
00:07:12,440 --> 00:07:18,200
But it was always, you know, sometimes I'd get stuff published, but it was always freelance, always on the edge of stuff.

80
00:07:18,200 --> 00:07:23,300
And probably by about 2010, I think I was actually ready to give up with journalism.

81
00:07:23,300 --> 00:07:37,540
I was ready, you know, it wasn't, because honestly, it was something that I was doing as a sort of holding pattern until I could figure out what was something, a more in-depth, intense intellectual engagement, right?

82
00:07:37,540 --> 00:07:42,340
Because journalism is not generally a place for big ideas.

83
00:07:42,720 --> 00:07:43,660
That's not what it's for.

84
00:07:43,660 --> 00:07:44,860
It's for what's happening right now.

85
00:07:45,500 --> 00:07:47,080
And I was always interested in the big ideas.

86
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:51,120
But there's some space for that in journalism, but not as much as I'd like, right?

87
00:07:51,120 --> 00:07:55,660
So, but then what I saw happening was the Arab Spring taking off in Cairo.

88
00:07:55,660 --> 00:07:58,300
And I thought, well, this is the story of a lifetime.

89
00:07:58,300 --> 00:08:00,360
This is something I would never have expected.

90
00:08:00,360 --> 00:08:01,180
It took me by shock.

91
00:08:01,440 --> 00:08:06,620
I had had a much more cynical and depressed out, you know, pessimistic outlook for the Arab world.

92
00:08:06,620 --> 00:08:08,500
And some would say that that's been confirmed.

93
00:08:08,500 --> 00:08:11,880
But I don't think, I think we actually learned something else.

94
00:08:11,880 --> 00:08:19,320
And, you know, we're getting towards the app now because I think people learned the wrong lessons from the Arab Spring, right?

95
00:08:19,320 --> 00:08:20,840
I think people learned all the wrong things.

96
00:08:20,960 --> 00:08:23,460
I think people got it wrong at the time.

97
00:08:23,460 --> 00:08:24,120
So there was this moment.

98
00:08:24,340 --> 00:08:32,140
I mean, my background is that, you know, my mom was a public servant, my dad's a left-wing bookseller, and I grew up in the inner west of Sydney.

99
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:36,020
So right in the sort of SBS left-wing demographic, right?

100
00:08:36,020 --> 00:08:40,880
So I grew up sort of on no Chomsky in media theory.

101
00:08:41,880 --> 00:08:50,280
And I would now, I would describe the way I behaved back then is that I was what you would call a Chomsky and counter propagandist, right?

102
00:08:50,280 --> 00:09:01,980
So you're hyper aware that there's this big machine that's spewing all this propaganda and the way you, what you see your role to do is to push back against that and to give a counter narrative.

103
00:09:01,980 --> 00:09:06,020
And then, but that can devolve into this tactical kind of nothingness, right?

104
00:09:06,020 --> 00:09:18,960
So when I was in Cairo in about 2012, after the revolution had happened, after Mubarak had fallen, after one, two, three, four, five elections had happened and the Brotherhood had won, all of those elections, right?

105
00:09:18,960 --> 00:09:27,400
Then you had a situation where they were getting all of this flack from most, from the entire English-speaking media, right?

106
00:09:27,400 --> 00:09:32,420
They were being predicted as like, you know, the bad guys, right?

107
00:09:32,420 --> 00:09:37,640
And then I had a really interesting occasion where I was, I was drinking with a guy from a very right-wing publication.

108
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:42,360
I don't want to say which one, but this is like, you know, a financial press thing, right?

109
00:09:42,360 --> 00:09:46,980
It writes about, their focus is on the business interests, but we were like absolutely agreeing.

110
00:09:46,980 --> 00:09:50,860
It's like the Brotherhood in general have a strong mandate.

111
00:09:50,860 --> 00:09:52,400
They're still quite popular.

112
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:54,040
They should be allowed to finish their term.

113
00:09:54,040 --> 00:09:58,380
And if they don't finish their term, the military will take over and democracy is over.

114
00:09:58,380 --> 00:09:59,040
That's it.

115
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:10,000
And this was one time when all of a sudden I'm not arguing with this person, where people who have my political ideology would agree with me.

116
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:15,640
And this person over here who I disagree with on political ideology agrees with me about what's actually happening.

117
00:10:15,640 --> 00:10:20,240
And it's like events were overtaking our ideological lens.

118
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:23,140
And that was a unique, a new experience for me.

119
00:10:23,140 --> 00:10:26,700
And it was this thing where it's like, well, what actually matters now is who knows their shit.

120
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:27,860
And that's about it.

121
00:10:27,860 --> 00:10:37,920
Because it's actually all about who's been paying attention and who's been doing the work, and who has been basing their reporting on what's on Twitter and English.

122
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:39,040
Right?

123
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:48,000
And this guy was from the financial press, so I shouldn't have agreed with him about, and he was quite right-wing, sort of Ron Paul kind of guy, right?

124
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:49,080
So we wouldn't have agreed about anything.

125
00:10:49,080 --> 00:10:50,800
And then I was like, I think that was the seed of it.

126
00:10:50,800 --> 00:11:08,140
And then when the coup happened and it was just as bad as everything we thought it would be, it became inefficient and insufficient for me to keep just writing blogs and trying to do that, be this one little voice, shouting into this stadium of other people who were also shouting.

127
00:11:08,140 --> 00:11:09,920
So the idea started building up.

128
00:11:10,440 --> 00:11:10,980
Exactly.

129
00:11:10,980 --> 00:11:12,540
And so this is the background.

130
00:11:12,540 --> 00:11:20,080
This is when we decided, first thing we decided was we'll try and do transparent journalism by founding a new magazine, a new online magazine.

131
00:11:20,080 --> 00:11:24,720
We teamed up with a bunch of other journalists to make this content and make the content transparent.

132
00:11:24,820 --> 00:11:28,400
So we would show people how it had been created.

133
00:11:29,220 --> 00:11:29,980
What are the steps?

134
00:11:29,980 --> 00:11:33,380
And we thought we could do that with existing technology.

135
00:11:33,380 --> 00:11:36,220
And that turned out to be a data management nightmare.

136
00:11:36,220 --> 00:11:50,480
So then we decided, well, we tried to do it so that it was an NGO that was running the publication, and then we wanted to run in parallel to that in an open-source software project to develop the tools to make it better.

137
00:11:50,480 --> 00:11:51,620
That was the next step.

138
00:11:51,620 --> 00:11:55,440
And then we just didn't get tracked any engineers and no one worked on the thing.

139
00:11:55,440 --> 00:11:56,900
So at some stage, I said, well, screw this.

140
00:11:56,900 --> 00:11:57,840
I'm just going to make software.

141
00:11:57,840 --> 00:12:02,540
I'll stop being creative about everything and just be creative about the product.

142
00:12:02,540 --> 00:12:15,200
And set up, and in 2017, founded the company, which only just now, nearly four years later, has released a product that we think is almost ready for commercial applications.

143
00:12:15,200 --> 00:12:16,600
So that's the story.

144
00:12:16,600 --> 00:12:18,720
Pardon me for maybe longer than you wanted.

145
00:12:19,480 --> 00:12:24,740
So this is this Write In Stone app you were talking about, definitely.

146
00:12:24,740 --> 00:12:25,500
Yeah.

147
00:12:25,500 --> 00:12:26,540
Yeah, that's Write In Stone.

148
00:12:26,540 --> 00:12:27,500
I mean, I just call it Stone.

149
00:12:27,500 --> 00:12:33,780
The company is called Write In Stone PTY Ltd, because Stone PTY Ltd was taken.

150
00:12:33,780 --> 00:12:36,980
Of course, stone.com is taken, and Stone on Twitter.

151
00:12:36,980 --> 00:12:41,400
So we have to call, so Write In Stone is the current general handle.

152
00:12:42,260 --> 00:12:47,460
And try to name it as stoner.com probably doesn't quite work as well.

153
00:12:47,460 --> 00:12:48,040
Yeah.

154
00:12:48,040 --> 00:12:53,880
Maybe once we're really huge, we can afford to buy these domains and handles of people and we'll just be able to be stone.com.

155
00:12:53,880 --> 00:13:03,440
So it's Write In Stone, as in writeinstone.com, if people want to go and download the beta.

156
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:10,740
And that is a, at the moment, it's an open beta, is what we're calling it, right?

157
00:13:10,740 --> 00:13:15,480
So we're not commercializing it at the moment.

158
00:13:15,480 --> 00:13:18,220
We're just letting people play with it and give us feedback.

159
00:13:18,220 --> 00:13:20,800
So ultimately, what is this app?

160
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:28,760
Like we now got the general background of like, what got you interested and now you have a problem you need to solve.

161
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:31,480
What is this thing that you just developed?

162
00:13:32,200 --> 00:13:39,540
Well, would you like me to show you, like on those cooking shows they do, here's one we prepared earlier.

163
00:13:39,540 --> 00:13:40,120
That works.

164
00:13:40,120 --> 00:13:41,660
If you could screen share.

165
00:13:41,660 --> 00:13:47,000
But don't forget that I may be doing an audio recording, so you may also need to describe it as well.

166
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:47,660
Yeah, okay.

167
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:50,920
Well, screen share so you can see it and you can help me describe it.

168
00:13:50,920 --> 00:13:54,860
Because sometimes it's easy, it's hard to describe it because you know it so well.

169
00:13:54,860 --> 00:13:57,700
Here's a presentation about it, but we'll come back to that in a second.

170
00:13:58,260 --> 00:14:04,160
And I'll show you an actual story that we've done with it at thebestdisinfectant.com.

171
00:14:04,160 --> 00:14:12,940
Now, we set this up, we set up a blog called thebestdisinfectant.com, because our product can be a standalone deliverable.

172
00:14:12,940 --> 00:14:15,500
You can just track the research and share that.

173
00:14:15,500 --> 00:14:24,740
But what we're really interested in doing is integrating with existing journalism workflows to sort of provide what I call epistemological struts.

174
00:14:26,860 --> 00:14:32,380
It's something to help bolster the credibility of existing content.

175
00:14:32,380 --> 00:14:34,820
So here we've got a story, it's a fact check story.

176
00:14:34,820 --> 00:14:48,520
And what we've done is we've got an off-the-shelf wordpress.com blog here, businessplanwordpress.comblog, and I've written a normal fact check here, or a fact check this video by Australian comedian Friendly Jordies.

177
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:50,200
So like a normal article?

178
00:14:50,200 --> 00:14:51,280
Yeah, just like a normal article.

179
00:14:51,680 --> 00:14:57,320
And down here, you can see the research portal is what we're calling it.

180
00:14:57,340 --> 00:15:00,560
And here you can see information.

181
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:13,020
The research duration is 494 minutes, which is about eight hours, six events, which means six periods when I was recording my research process, and 59 highlights.

182
00:15:13,020 --> 00:15:14,740
And you can click through and view that.

183
00:15:14,740 --> 00:15:19,480
But first, just while you're in the article, we have to have what we call the highlights.

184
00:15:19,480 --> 00:15:33,420
So as I'm doing my research process, at any point that I think is a key turning point, or if I think I found information that's going to be key to my story, I turn on my webcam and I add a little commentary.

185
00:15:33,420 --> 00:15:34,160
So we've got one here.

186
00:15:36,400 --> 00:15:45,960
So I'm going to fact check Friendly Jordy's today, not because I don't like the channel, but because I do.

187
00:15:45,960 --> 00:15:47,720
And I can skip to the next.

188
00:15:50,080 --> 00:15:51,220
vaccinations.

189
00:15:51,220 --> 00:15:52,400
Now I'm no doctor.

190
00:15:52,520 --> 00:15:53,620
I'm a doctor of beads.

191
00:15:54,660 --> 00:15:55,460
Oh yeah.

192
00:15:55,460 --> 00:15:56,780
But I'm not a medical doctor.

193
00:15:56,780 --> 00:16:05,620
However, I think the reason that we have a 7% rollout might have something to do with the fact that Scott Borrissett seems to have bought our entire vaccination supply.

194
00:16:05,620 --> 00:16:09,000
So that's him talking and has me identifying the fact that I'm going to check.

195
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:13,860
And you can go through all of these little highlights to see the bits where I'm talking.

196
00:16:13,860 --> 00:16:18,920
Or you can click through here to the full research project, which opens in a separate page.

197
00:16:18,920 --> 00:16:23,400
And you can turn on full research playback.

198
00:16:23,400 --> 00:16:29,080
And so that means, for example, here is a session where I sat down and I did some more research.

199
00:16:30,440 --> 00:16:31,000
Right.

200
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:32,100
But I didn't add a highlight.

201
00:16:32,380 --> 00:16:33,900
So it's just me checking something out.

202
00:16:33,900 --> 00:16:35,900
And this is what I've got.

203
00:16:35,900 --> 00:16:40,020
This is now an audit trail of the claim that I make.

204
00:16:40,020 --> 00:16:43,900
So it's not just video and this is kind of like a timeline.

205
00:16:44,480 --> 00:16:46,260
For now, it's video.

206
00:16:46,260 --> 00:16:48,500
Well, we're going to start adding other formats.

207
00:16:48,500 --> 00:16:53,060
But the first thing we're starting with is video and within that screen capture.

208
00:16:53,060 --> 00:16:56,420
But we're not a technology focused company, we're a mission focused company.

209
00:16:56,420 --> 00:17:00,100
So whatever helps us capture research, that's what we're going to do.

210
00:17:00,340 --> 00:17:06,520
And we've got a whole bunch of ideas for how this goes beyond any particular technology at the time.

211
00:17:06,520 --> 00:17:14,960
But the point of this is that when I say it's an audit trail, what I mean is that the person, if someone wants to know how did I reach this conclusion, right?

212
00:17:14,960 --> 00:17:16,099
They can go back and look through it.

213
00:17:16,099 --> 00:17:27,700
And see, imagining what becomes apparent is not just a degree of diligence, are you doing your homework, but your intent becomes more apparent.

214
00:17:27,700 --> 00:17:30,620
And if your intentions are good, then that's a good thing.

215
00:17:30,620 --> 00:17:33,220
And then this becomes a force multiply for you.

216
00:17:33,220 --> 00:17:37,360
Because, you know, it's a information-rich format, right?

217
00:17:37,360 --> 00:17:49,780
There's a lot of information here, but it's also a social format because it's based on, you see the journalists face, you hear them talk, and they're explaining, these are the decision, this is how I'm making the research decisions I need to make as I go along, right?

218
00:17:49,780 --> 00:17:59,160
And what I believe is even if people get it wrong, if you see that they've done it using, that they were acting in good faith, right?

219
00:17:59,160 --> 00:18:06,280
And that they're making themselves accountable to you, you're going to be more forgiving about when they get it wrong, and there's going to be more of a sense of rapport and trust.

220
00:18:06,280 --> 00:18:12,920
You know, it's actually an emotional problem at its core, a lot of what's going on.

221
00:18:12,920 --> 00:18:24,200
I wonder if there's a certain similarity between this kind of philosophy you're talking about regarding what you want to bring to journalism to, like say, how people do investigation in the legal system.

222
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:26,900
Yeah, exactly.

223
00:18:26,900 --> 00:18:32,040
And I mean, we've had interest from law enforcement for a version of this.

224
00:18:32,040 --> 00:18:39,220
And now there's already products sort of focused on the law enforcement use case for this that what they'll do is index.

225
00:18:39,220 --> 00:18:41,020
You know, Hunchley is the big one, right?

226
00:18:41,020 --> 00:18:44,560
And some of the people that we would like to target are using Hunchley.

227
00:18:44,560 --> 00:18:50,400
Hunchley is a Chrome browser extension, and it copies the web pages that you're using.

228
00:18:50,540 --> 00:19:00,680
So that if, you know, and it's used, like, for example, a police officer might use it to make a copy of a website where someone says, hey, I'm going to, you know, f-ing kill you, right?

229
00:19:00,680 --> 00:19:01,240
Or whatever.

230
00:19:01,240 --> 00:19:05,560
And then while they're drunk, before they take it down the next morning, well, it doesn't matter.

231
00:19:05,560 --> 00:19:07,460
I've got proof that they made that threat.

232
00:19:07,460 --> 00:19:08,000
Right.

233
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:09,880
And that could be relevant for a lot.

234
00:19:10,200 --> 00:19:13,440
And it's indexed with like a PGP key or something like that.

235
00:19:15,180 --> 00:19:19,440
So the veracity of the records is vouched for by Hunchley, the company.

236
00:19:19,860 --> 00:19:20,760
Right.

237
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:21,380
So that's what that is.

238
00:19:21,380 --> 00:19:24,040
And that's the most similar product on the market.

239
00:19:24,040 --> 00:19:28,680
Now, I don't think people who are using Hunchley should stop using Hunchley and use us.

240
00:19:28,680 --> 00:19:34,300
I think they should keep using Hunchley and show everybody else how to use Hunchley using us.

241
00:19:34,300 --> 00:19:34,640
Right.

242
00:19:34,640 --> 00:19:35,240
That's what I want.

243
00:19:35,240 --> 00:19:52,700
I want to be a force multiplier for all the existing tools, to be a delivery system so that people can show each other how to use these tools effectively, just as part of the ordinary workflow, rather than in separate tutorials or whatever.

244
00:19:52,700 --> 00:19:59,680
Kind of curious, it sounds like there is something similar like Hunchley, but are journalists using these things as well?

245
00:19:59,680 --> 00:20:08,060
Some people are using Hunchley, and some journalists are using Hunchley, some very sophisticated, technologically inclined journalists.

246
00:20:08,060 --> 00:20:16,160
And we want to expand that kind of good information hygiene, and we see ourselves as a vector for that.

247
00:20:17,200 --> 00:20:20,080
But that's not public-facing, that's for court.

248
00:20:20,080 --> 00:20:22,460
And it doesn't solve any...

249
00:20:22,560 --> 00:20:23,520
It's also something...

250
00:20:23,520 --> 00:20:27,540
They also charge money for their product, and people pay to use it.

251
00:20:27,540 --> 00:20:30,360
And because it's private, that's a good model.

252
00:20:30,360 --> 00:20:36,560
But what we are hoping to do is once we start to build up a good volume of use, is we'll actually pay our users.

253
00:20:36,560 --> 00:20:47,820
We'll put advertising content in the video as a pre-roll, and then that will be a way for journalists to monetize this work, which is at the moment a net cost.

254
00:20:47,820 --> 00:20:56,820
So at the moment, if you're investing in research, you're doing it for this long-term goal of the prestige of your organization.

255
00:20:57,720 --> 00:21:22,340
So what happens is someone at a premium tier journalistic outfit, one of the people who have a real sense of pride in what they're doing, they will invest 8 hours, 10 hours, 40 hours, 400 hours in deep dive investigative work, and then they publish it, and 25 minutes later, thousands of people have copied it if it's really good stuff.

256
00:21:22,340 --> 00:21:27,240
And as a consumer, it's not immediately obvious who did the work and who didn't.

257
00:21:27,240 --> 00:21:30,960
So that's why we say research is valuable, make it visible.

258
00:21:30,960 --> 00:21:37,580
So A, you're going to have a stronger impact on your brand using this product, you're going to have a stronger impact.

259
00:21:38,360 --> 00:21:44,940
People are going to associate the research work with your brand directly because they can see it on your website.

260
00:21:44,940 --> 00:21:52,100
And two, you're going to have this video content, which is actually relevant, actually informative, and goes with the article.

261
00:21:52,100 --> 00:21:54,860
And that's an increase in productivity.

262
00:21:55,760 --> 00:22:02,740
That sort of reminds me of artists, basically live streaming their development of art in some ways.

263
00:22:02,740 --> 00:22:13,080
And I have a feeling it's slightly related to how a lot of arts are being copied, and so the attribution gets lost very easily.

264
00:22:13,080 --> 00:22:27,200
But if you have a live stream recording of you doing the art, not only is it just extra entertainment, but it also provides an immutable record that you did the work.

265
00:22:27,200 --> 00:22:28,360
Yeah.

266
00:22:28,360 --> 00:22:29,020
See, this is the thing.

267
00:22:29,020 --> 00:22:34,200
It's like, why are guys in high-vis construction, workers on the road have to wear high-vis?

268
00:22:34,200 --> 00:22:37,960
Because visibility is a kind of protection, right?

269
00:22:37,960 --> 00:22:51,600
And if your evidence trail and your good faith efforts are visible, then that protects you from attacks in the sense of attacks on your character, right?

270
00:22:51,600 --> 00:23:03,920
And if your process of creating original work is visible, that protects you from people disputing your ownership of the finished product, right?

271
00:23:03,920 --> 00:23:08,240
And there's a kind of openness and reflexivity to it.

272
00:23:08,240 --> 00:23:14,940
That is not what we're doing is actually bringing things that have happened in other places to journalism, right?

273
00:23:15,020 --> 00:23:20,960
So, Twitch has already got screen capture, porn has already got webcams, right?

274
00:23:20,960 --> 00:23:25,120
And that's what happens, and you're talking about in art, right?

275
00:23:25,120 --> 00:23:29,140
This technology comes to journalism last normally.

276
00:23:30,340 --> 00:23:35,600
So, one of our challenges is that the journalists are not early adopters of technology, right?

277
00:23:35,600 --> 00:23:42,280
But they were eventually dragged onto the web, and they were eventually dragged onto social media, and they're being dragged into video, right?

278
00:23:43,420 --> 00:23:54,240
And we're both part of that thing where they're being dragged into video, and that morphing into something else, where they're dragged into this kind of hyper-transparent accountability.

279
00:23:54,240 --> 00:23:55,880
Not in every situation.

280
00:23:55,880 --> 00:23:57,460
Sometimes you need secrecy.

281
00:23:57,460 --> 00:24:05,840
But when you don't need secrecy, you shouldn't default to it if your job is to engage with the public and convince them of things.

282
00:24:05,840 --> 00:24:10,860
Not just tell them things, but show them the respect of convincing them and presenting the evidence.

283
00:24:12,380 --> 00:24:20,640
Is there a certain conservatism inherit in the industry which is causing them to lag behind in adoption or evolution?

284
00:24:20,640 --> 00:24:26,480
Because in some ways, people feel like that media or journalism is a...

285
00:24:26,480 --> 00:24:28,760
They're not really keeping up with the times.

286
00:24:28,780 --> 00:24:32,100
And this is what you're probably trying to address.

287
00:24:32,340 --> 00:24:41,680
But I'm kind of curious as to, like, have you been talking to your journalistic community, which you're part of, and have any insight as to why this is the case?

288
00:24:41,680 --> 00:24:50,220
Yeah, I don't want to try and characterize the journalism community broadly, because it's a very complicated question.

289
00:24:50,220 --> 00:24:51,820
And I'm not...

290
00:24:51,820 --> 00:24:56,040
I haven't been that much in touch with the journalistic community for a while now, right?

291
00:24:56,200 --> 00:24:58,360
So first, when we...

292
00:25:00,600 --> 00:25:02,420
Well, one thing that happened is I left...

293
00:25:02,420 --> 00:25:06,760
Most of my journalism work was either in the Middle East or, you know, New South Wales, right?

294
00:25:06,760 --> 00:25:10,920
And then in 2013, when I left Egypt, I didn't come home.

295
00:25:10,920 --> 00:25:12,740
I went to Ecuador.

296
00:25:12,740 --> 00:25:13,860
And so...

297
00:25:13,860 --> 00:25:21,920
And like everyone told me it was a bad idea as a journalist, because what happens is the world pages is 2% of coverage or something like that.

298
00:25:21,920 --> 00:25:28,220
And then 80% of that's the Middle East and the rest is America, actually, or Europe, right?

299
00:25:28,240 --> 00:25:36,700
And so it's really difficult to get stuff published from Latin America.

300
00:25:37,140 --> 00:25:38,700
And so that was the beginning of it.

301
00:25:38,700 --> 00:25:49,680
I mean, I was still sort of doing some work, but then we started on this project and I've kind of, I haven't really been in the loop with journalists for a long time, and it's a rapidly changing landscape.

302
00:25:49,680 --> 00:25:54,960
My impression is that you've really got to think in generations, right?

303
00:25:55,400 --> 00:26:00,320
And so there's this boomer generation who are quite conservative and the hardest to work with.

304
00:26:00,320 --> 00:26:05,720
Then there's our generation, the 90s boomers is what the kids are calling us now.

305
00:26:05,720 --> 00:26:10,920
And I think they're on to something, the more I pay attention.

306
00:26:10,920 --> 00:26:15,240
But I'll show you another use case that we've got.

307
00:26:16,640 --> 00:26:17,640
Do I have it here?

308
00:26:17,640 --> 00:26:19,180
No, hold on a sec.

309
00:26:19,180 --> 00:26:25,620
Let me see if I can pull it up because, yes, here we go.

310
00:26:26,680 --> 00:26:29,940
Oh yeah, you have a new client.

311
00:26:29,940 --> 00:26:31,180
Yeah.

312
00:26:31,180 --> 00:26:41,120
Well, hopefully, this is patient zero, because we built a version, we had some journalists use it, and then it essentially wasn't quite good enough, right?

313
00:26:41,120 --> 00:26:46,860
And there was technical sort of deep, boring code reasons for that, and we had to take it all apart and rebuild it.

314
00:26:46,860 --> 00:26:48,740
And we've done that now.

315
00:26:48,740 --> 00:27:06,880
So this is our open beta that's only been online a few weeks, and this is sort of the first person outside our sort of immediate clique of friends and people who are actually in the company to give it what I would call a load-bearing test, where they're actually trying to tell a story with it.

316
00:27:06,880 --> 00:27:17,160
And this is Scott Stedman, who runs a place called the Forensic News, which shows, I'll pull them up actually, Forensic News.

317
00:27:20,780 --> 00:27:23,180
And they've got this sort of these three principles.

318
00:27:24,200 --> 00:27:25,460
Hold on.

319
00:27:25,480 --> 00:27:26,740
It's struggling with Zoom.

320
00:27:26,740 --> 00:27:30,260
Forensic News, Modern Investigative Journalism.

321
00:27:30,280 --> 00:27:32,360
And let's go to about.

322
00:27:32,360 --> 00:27:37,820
They have, there's evidence is key.

323
00:27:37,820 --> 00:27:38,780
Articles are always free.

324
00:27:38,980 --> 00:27:41,180
Clicks should not equal profit, right?

325
00:27:42,500 --> 00:27:45,840
There's a free press dies behind paywalls.

326
00:27:45,840 --> 00:27:47,040
But this evidence is key.

327
00:27:47,040 --> 00:27:55,440
And this sort of emphasis on being public facing, it shows that there's a similar ethos that other people are thinking.

328
00:27:55,440 --> 00:27:57,980
People are thinking along the same lines as us.

329
00:27:57,980 --> 00:27:59,400
And they're younger people.

330
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:04,960
They're, you know, this guy's, I'm not sure how old he is, but he's definitely a lot younger than me.

331
00:28:06,420 --> 00:28:17,640
And he's, you know, he's doing really well in terms of already doing great work, which is heavily research driven.

332
00:28:17,640 --> 00:28:26,700
And we can unlock that and help him stand out and show that he, and help emphasize his points of difference.

333
00:28:26,700 --> 00:28:29,320
Like I said before, the word is force multiplier.

334
00:28:29,320 --> 00:28:36,500
And we're a force multiplier for this research work he's doing right here, which otherwise would have been 155 minutes of it.

335
00:28:36,500 --> 00:28:42,680
So otherwise would have been only spoken of, not seen directly by the end user.

336
00:28:44,060 --> 00:28:51,520
Well, we definitely need more people like asking the fundamental question of like can we trust what we see or read?

337
00:28:51,520 --> 00:28:57,200
So I think people are asking that question, and that's a good thing.

338
00:28:57,900 --> 00:29:05,640
And that it had the bad consequence because there's this transition to a new set of norms which hasn't happened yet.

339
00:29:05,640 --> 00:29:11,640
And it's actually a good thing that the, because the New York Times said so is no longer good enough, right?

340
00:29:11,640 --> 00:29:15,480
Or because Twitter said so is no longer good enough, right?

341
00:29:15,480 --> 00:29:20,780
I mean, I don't know to what extent it ever was considered good enough.

342
00:29:20,780 --> 00:29:24,000
But we shouldn't have this idealization of the old system.

343
00:29:24,080 --> 00:29:30,980
But there's something I'll say about that is that, so the old system was described well by Chomsky.

344
00:29:30,980 --> 00:29:37,720
He says, you know, you've got a sort of, it's sort of a goalposts system where you have someone on the, someone who marks the leftward boundary.

345
00:29:37,720 --> 00:29:42,960
So say Bernie Sanders marks the leftward boundary of acceptable public discourse.

346
00:29:42,960 --> 00:29:45,540
And that's further left than it was a little while ago.

347
00:29:45,540 --> 00:29:51,340
And on the right, you've got, I don't know, somebody else who marks the furthest right point of public discourse.

348
00:29:51,460 --> 00:29:55,480
And what's between those two points is reasonable debate.

349
00:29:55,480 --> 00:30:01,440
And what's agreed on by the people between those two points is an established consensus.

350
00:30:01,440 --> 00:30:02,580
Right?

351
00:30:02,580 --> 00:30:05,820
And that was the model and there were a lot of problems with that model.

352
00:30:05,820 --> 00:30:11,100
Now we've got a model where there are no goalposts and there is no consensus and everything's falling apart.

353
00:30:11,100 --> 00:30:13,300
And that's not great either.

354
00:30:13,300 --> 00:30:13,580
Right?

355
00:30:13,580 --> 00:30:23,260
That's also, and that's actually very useful to bad actors, to authoritarians and criminals and, you know, cynical bad faith actors.

356
00:30:23,260 --> 00:30:27,400
The more, you know, like little finger in Game of Thrones says, chaos is a ladder.

357
00:30:27,400 --> 00:30:29,180
Right?

358
00:30:29,180 --> 00:30:42,160
So this is the way to try and bring order to that chaos without re-establishing institutional control and without saying, okay, what we're going to do is we're going to have a bunch of experts say, this is real and that's not real.

359
00:30:42,160 --> 00:30:50,100
And you, Joe Schmo at home, you listen to what you're told and you don't, you know, think, you know, better than you're betters, right?

360
00:30:50,100 --> 00:30:54,080
That's, that's not, that's an intellectually bankrupt position.

361
00:30:54,080 --> 00:30:58,540
So the answer is more openness and more engagement.

362
00:30:58,540 --> 00:31:00,680
Actually, this is a great time to jump to my little presentation.

363
00:31:00,680 --> 00:31:02,180
Do you mind?

364
00:31:02,180 --> 00:31:03,620
Yeah, go ahead.

365
00:31:04,720 --> 00:31:07,900
So this is a presentation I'm working on.

366
00:31:07,900 --> 00:31:10,400
You can consider this a sneak preview, right?

367
00:31:10,820 --> 00:31:12,820
We've got knowledge quality and the public sphere.

368
00:31:12,820 --> 00:31:21,160
So you can imagine that this is the old way of doing things.

369
00:31:21,160 --> 00:31:29,180
You have on the left here the subject matter, I beg your pardon, the subject matter, which is the actual story, the real world, right?

370
00:31:29,180 --> 00:31:33,260
And you have a cone of information that extends away from that.

371
00:31:33,480 --> 00:31:36,920
And the further you are from the events, the less information you have.

372
00:31:37,400 --> 00:31:41,060
And at the other end is the general public, right?

373
00:31:41,060 --> 00:31:45,180
And coming away from the general public is an attention cone.

374
00:31:46,200 --> 00:31:53,600
So and where those two cones intersect, where attention and information meet, that's what I'm calling public knowledge, right?

375
00:31:53,600 --> 00:31:55,100
And at the center of that is journalism.

376
00:31:55,100 --> 00:31:56,240
This is the olden days.

377
00:31:56,240 --> 00:32:00,300
This is how it worked in, you know, in 1989, right?

378
00:32:00,300 --> 00:32:02,120
Or maybe even earlier, I don't care.

379
00:32:02,120 --> 00:32:08,620
But look, now what would have happened is social media has come into the picture, and that's moved the center of gravity of the system.

380
00:32:08,620 --> 00:32:13,200
It's moved the center of activity in the direction of the general public, right?

381
00:32:13,200 --> 00:32:15,660
And that's probably mostly a good thing.

382
00:32:15,660 --> 00:32:19,160
But there are issues with it, right?

383
00:32:19,160 --> 00:32:34,880
One of the things that's happened, and there's been various attempts to fix the fake news problem which act in this side of the, which take place in this side of the map here, right?

384
00:32:34,880 --> 00:32:47,660
They'll take a story after it's published and look at either using an algorithm or experts or whatever they'll try and then get between the story and the general public and act as a filter, right?

385
00:32:48,060 --> 00:32:51,760
And that's not an approach we're saying shouldn't be tried at all.

386
00:32:51,760 --> 00:33:04,820
We're saying what we also want to do, what we want to do is also have research content over here further from the general public closer to the actual subject matter, which then rebalances the system, right?

387
00:33:04,820 --> 00:33:12,380
So and of course, you bring the general public, this more information reaches the general public in this model as well, right?

388
00:33:12,380 --> 00:33:19,700
So this becomes visible, it becomes structured, it becomes something that you can look out and talk about.

389
00:33:19,720 --> 00:33:36,440
And so where other places are on top of or in front of rather the, sorry, where other places are in top of or in front of this new story, we're behind and below.

390
00:33:36,440 --> 00:33:39,400
So you want to show the iceberg, right?

391
00:33:41,700 --> 00:33:42,420
Yeah, exactly.

392
00:33:43,820 --> 00:33:51,140
Most of it's hidden, and there's the most information here, and the smallest number of people will look at it compared to the top layer.

393
00:33:51,140 --> 00:33:53,400
Most people will look at the tweet.

394
00:33:53,400 --> 00:34:03,980
Fewer people than that will look at the story, and the smallest number will look at this, but that will have the highest quality of engagement, because it will have the most detail, you know exactly where the information came from, right?

395
00:34:04,480 --> 00:34:17,580
And then those people can feed back into their reviews, maybe have reviews or whatever, but even now they can just talk about the quality of the research that occurred on existing channels like Reddit or Twitter or whatever.

396
00:34:17,580 --> 00:34:23,040
And that will begin a conversation about what's an acceptably checked fact.

397
00:34:23,040 --> 00:34:24,340
What does that mean?

398
00:34:24,340 --> 00:34:24,920
Right?

399
00:34:24,920 --> 00:34:27,179
And we're going to get forensic about what that means.

400
00:34:27,179 --> 00:34:36,699
So, you know, the other way to imagine it, there's a canoe and that's the original news article that actually transports the headline, right, the cargo.

401
00:34:36,699 --> 00:34:44,340
And then social media is like a sail that's been reached, that transports it further and moves it faster, right?

402
00:34:44,340 --> 00:34:52,239
But also makes it more prone to capsize, makes it more prone to getting blown around by powerful winds, right?

403
00:34:52,239 --> 00:34:54,000
So what we are is the keel.

404
00:34:54,000 --> 00:35:04,700
We're on the other side adding a small amount of friction, actually, and creating, you know, stability in the process and giving stability to the information ecosystem.

405
00:35:04,700 --> 00:35:08,580
And that is, you know, this is the basic approach we want to take.

406
00:35:08,580 --> 00:35:12,540
And, you know, you've seen the actual thing, you've seen the theoretical framework.

407
00:35:12,540 --> 00:35:13,520
Any questions?

408
00:35:13,520 --> 00:35:16,100
What you showed was pretty fascinating.

409
00:35:16,100 --> 00:35:19,600
And this is another guy that you showed called Forensic Nils.

410
00:35:19,600 --> 00:35:24,000
It poked my head about this other group called Forensic Architecture.

411
00:35:24,000 --> 00:35:34,380
And what I like about Forensic Architecture is that they show a 3D space and how they are able to derive based on lots of different media articles.

412
00:35:34,380 --> 00:35:35,540
What happened?

413
00:35:35,540 --> 00:35:39,620
Like social media videos, for example, the Buried explosion.

414
00:35:39,620 --> 00:35:45,460
But what I would also like to have known is the underlying research methodology.

415
00:35:45,460 --> 00:35:54,380
And how did they piece all to get all these media videos from the public to create a cohesive snapshot of what actually happened on that day?

416
00:35:54,380 --> 00:35:57,920
Yeah, look, I want that almost more.

417
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:01,880
You know, they're one of the people in the world I would most love to get using this tool.

418
00:36:01,880 --> 00:36:03,220
Oh, you heard about these guys?

419
00:36:03,220 --> 00:36:04,560
I've known about them.

420
00:36:04,560 --> 00:36:14,880
I actually, first time I heard about them, I met a guy in Ecuador from the team who was visiting, and I've been fascinated by them ever since.

421
00:36:14,880 --> 00:36:22,380
And I'm sure there's been some email exchanges with them, maybe with the last version or something like that.

422
00:36:22,380 --> 00:36:24,660
But they're the kind of people we want to get using this.

423
00:36:26,640 --> 00:36:29,900
Are you in touch with them by any chance?

424
00:36:29,900 --> 00:36:32,400
Are you in touch with them by any chance?

425
00:36:32,400 --> 00:36:35,220
Well, I'm in touch with them, and they're not that in touch with me back.

426
00:36:36,920 --> 00:36:37,740
It's a bit like...

427
00:36:38,620 --> 00:36:41,960
It's a big change that we're asking people to embrace here.

428
00:36:41,960 --> 00:36:44,560
And it's about finding who's going to be that first person on the dance floor.

429
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:53,220
And it's literally just today with this new version, we've had Scott, our first person, get on the dance floor.

430
00:36:53,220 --> 00:37:05,480
But I think he's an excellent first user, and which is important to us because the early users you get, they become part of your company's DNA because you build for them, right?

431
00:37:05,480 --> 00:37:06,840
And so we've been very...

432
00:37:06,840 --> 00:37:12,900
That's one of the reasons we're not advertising, and I'm basically going around bothering people who are very busy people, right?

433
00:37:13,840 --> 00:37:16,420
Saying, hey, please look at my app.

434
00:37:16,420 --> 00:37:17,580
I think it's going to change the world.

435
00:37:17,580 --> 00:37:19,660
And they're like, yeah, cool story, bro, right?

436
00:37:19,660 --> 00:37:23,780
But I think it's going to be like pushing a boulder off a hill, right?

437
00:37:23,800 --> 00:37:40,360
Once it's hard to get it moving, but once it starts going, it's going to be unstoppable because originally it's a novelty where it's like, oh, wow, this person's making themselves accountable and they're explaining themselves in this really rigorous way, right?

438
00:37:40,360 --> 00:37:47,200
And that'll be a novelty and then more people will use it and then slowly becomes, well, why aren't people doing this by default, right?

439
00:37:47,200 --> 00:37:54,040
Like obviously there are times you have to protect someone's identity or something like that, but that's not most of journalism, right?

440
00:37:54,040 --> 00:37:56,780
Like that's not most of knowledge production, right?

441
00:37:56,780 --> 00:38:01,760
Like mostly knowledge is produced in a civic public space, right?

442
00:38:02,580 --> 00:38:11,600
And very rarely do you have to put on a trench coat and go down to a dark alley to be handed a manila folder by a man, you know, smoking a cigarette.

443
00:38:11,600 --> 00:38:18,240
So perhaps we're not actually creating something new, we're merely bringing it back to what it originally was.

444
00:38:18,240 --> 00:38:20,660
Well, that's, I mean, it's old principles, right?

445
00:38:20,840 --> 00:38:29,180
I have been saying that there's a fundamental enlightenment principle of strength through vulnerability, right?

446
00:38:29,180 --> 00:38:32,180
Government should be electable, so they can be kicked out of office.

447
00:38:32,180 --> 00:38:34,920
Their vulnerability makes the system...

448
00:38:34,940 --> 00:38:44,080
I'm going to go ahead and start with the first one, which is, you know, the idea of falsifiability.

449
00:38:44,080 --> 00:38:52,600
So, you know, if you get anything but the experiment results you predicted, your theory has been falsified, and it's not real, right?

450
00:38:52,600 --> 00:38:59,020
But because of that extreme vulnerability, when it survives, there's the meaning of that is really strong.

451
00:38:59,020 --> 00:39:08,260
And, you know, then we have bibliographies in academia that's not scientific, like in the humanities, and that's about making it easier to check if you're lying, right?

452
00:39:08,260 --> 00:39:15,760
But I tell you what this was, I'm quoting this guy, and it's on this page of this year's edition of the book, right?

453
00:39:15,760 --> 00:39:18,340
So you can go find the edition and look and say, no, he didn't, he didn't say that.

454
00:39:18,340 --> 00:39:20,660
He said something else, or she, or whatever, right?

455
00:39:20,660 --> 00:39:25,100
And that's again, strength through vulnerability, right?

456
00:39:25,100 --> 00:39:32,820
And so that's what we're trying to bring to digital nonfiction, you know, day-to-day public knowledge creation.

457
00:39:32,820 --> 00:39:33,460
I see.

458
00:39:33,460 --> 00:39:44,640
Well, this also reminds me of you, have you remembered about a few years ago where the idea of putting cameras on police, body cameras were absolutely controversial?

459
00:39:44,640 --> 00:39:50,240
And some of the arguments I've heard by the police is, what if I need to bring it to the toilet?

460
00:39:50,240 --> 00:39:52,140
So you could go on from there.

461
00:39:52,140 --> 00:39:54,460
Yeah, well, I mean, we have a pause button, right?

462
00:39:54,480 --> 00:39:57,620
And we, it's not quite like a body cam on a cop.

463
00:39:58,840 --> 00:40:02,880
Because it's not this sort of, it's not like an external surveillance system.

464
00:40:02,880 --> 00:40:09,780
It's not like a camera that's watching a factory worker to make sure they don't, you know, pee in a bottle either, right?

465
00:40:09,780 --> 00:40:12,360
You turn it on and you turn it off.

466
00:40:12,360 --> 00:40:22,480
There may be, we're concerned, and we want to balance against this concern, that it might be used to overwork people, right?

467
00:40:22,480 --> 00:40:30,240
To say, well, in 12 hours, you've got to produce, you know, 10 hours and 15, 11 hours and 59 minutes of research content.

468
00:40:30,240 --> 00:40:35,760
And we want to, we're going to try and build in some ergonomic, you know, digital ergonomic.

469
00:40:35,780 --> 00:40:46,140
Oh, did you remember about, like, was it New York Time where they wanted to put a, like a sensor under the desk to check for presence of journalists on the desk?

470
00:40:46,140 --> 00:40:46,920
Wow.

471
00:40:46,920 --> 00:40:47,580
Yeah, no, we're not.

472
00:40:47,900 --> 00:40:58,040
I can't remember, I can't remember which, whether it was New York Time or, sorry, but it was like an outcry by the journalist, because like you could potentially use that data to figure out.

473
00:40:58,040 --> 00:40:58,200
Yeah.

474
00:40:58,200 --> 00:41:04,260
So, I mean, what we're, what we're trying to say, look, we are at the moment, one of the values we're calculating is the, is the time spent by the journalist.

475
00:41:04,260 --> 00:41:07,100
That's basically the only value we're adding, right?

476
00:41:07,100 --> 00:41:12,720
Next, we want to do ratings, and then we want to try and build slowly a sort of matrix of values.

477
00:41:12,720 --> 00:41:21,480
Like you have all these values about the weather, you have the temperature and the humidity and the, you know, the barometer barometric pressure or whatever it is.

478
00:41:21,480 --> 00:41:29,500
And once you have those multiple variables, you can start to make, you know, and then you've got this data, you can start to do all kinds of things, right?

479
00:41:29,500 --> 00:41:32,060
And we've got to start somewhere, and this was the easiest one.

480
00:41:32,060 --> 00:41:35,060
I mean, still quite, still becomes quite a challenge to define, okay?

481
00:41:35,060 --> 00:41:39,080
So what counts as research, as time spent researching?

482
00:41:39,080 --> 00:41:45,600
So for example, the highlights when someone's talking, we've recently decided that no, we're not going to count them as research time.

483
00:41:45,600 --> 00:41:48,300
When your mouth's moving, you're not researching, right?

484
00:41:48,300 --> 00:41:49,280
You're doing something else.

485
00:41:50,620 --> 00:41:56,600
You're then on the side where you're outputting, and what we're measuring is the input of information that you took, right?

486
00:41:56,600 --> 00:42:02,640
And of course, we're trying to streamline that inputting and outputting of information as well.

487
00:42:02,640 --> 00:42:11,120
So as you're going, you can output these little research notes, which are like tabs in a binder.

488
00:42:12,300 --> 00:42:18,760
But in terms of building that matrix of values, we don't even know what all of them are going to be yet.

489
00:42:18,760 --> 00:42:35,780
As we start to do stuff, we'll have more of an observable community to see what is it that actually differentiates people, and what's something that's interesting and worth measuring.

490
00:42:37,240 --> 00:42:38,360
Well, thank you very much.

491
00:42:38,580 --> 00:42:48,580
I think we've covered practically the whole concert of Write In Stone, and it's really fascinating, and I certainly hope it gets explored more and catches on with its own merit as well.

492
00:42:48,580 --> 00:42:49,340
Thank you very much.

493
00:42:49,340 --> 00:42:50,720
It's been a pleasure.

494
00:42:50,720 --> 00:42:52,760
Is there anything you would like to...

495
00:42:52,960 --> 00:42:58,560
Well, I mean, you know, people should go to www.writeinstone.com and play with it.

496
00:42:58,560 --> 00:43:06,340
If you're in the realm of trying to convince people of the facts, right?

497
00:43:06,820 --> 00:43:08,760
You know, last, here's how I'll say it.

498
00:43:08,760 --> 00:43:11,700
We're actually the anti Twitter and we're not against Twitter.

499
00:43:11,700 --> 00:43:13,600
They've got a place in the ecosystem.

500
00:43:13,600 --> 00:43:18,700
When you want to be, you know, fast and flippant and fun, you go to Twitter.

501
00:43:18,700 --> 00:43:22,800
And when you want to take your time and get it right, you use Stone.

502
00:43:22,820 --> 00:43:28,800
And it's a product that I think we've been hacking away at this for a while and our product has gotten better.

503
00:43:28,800 --> 00:43:31,420
And, you know, the environment is evolving too.

504
00:43:31,420 --> 00:43:33,760
And I think the market is ready for this tool now.

505
00:43:34,040 --> 00:43:44,800
You know, after Trump and the coronavirus and it just keeps getting worse, we struggle as a society, as a global society, to agree on what's true.

506
00:43:44,800 --> 00:43:46,740
And that's really dangerous.

507
00:43:46,740 --> 00:43:51,240
And I think our approach, other people want to build walls, right?

508
00:43:51,240 --> 00:43:53,260
They want to build walls and they want to build a fortress.

509
00:43:53,260 --> 00:43:58,300
And inside that fortress, you know, legacy journalism can starve to death slowly, right?

510
00:43:58,300 --> 00:44:04,860
Whereas what we want to do is build windows, not walls, and let people in, and let people see what's going on.

511
00:44:04,860 --> 00:44:05,280
But you know what?

512
00:44:05,280 --> 00:44:06,900
That's also going to let in some sunlight.

513
00:44:06,900 --> 00:44:13,100
And that's going to have, you know, the people who are now subject to scrutiny, you're going to have to behave a little bit better.

514
00:44:13,100 --> 00:44:20,660
And both that, you know, and that's how you can see people, you know, this rift between the audience and journalists can be healed.

515
00:44:20,660 --> 00:44:28,660
And ultimately, rebuild the trust between the audience and the journalist, so that the journalists can trust the public and the public can trust the journalist.

516
00:44:29,160 --> 00:44:34,880
Then we can hopefully start to have more intelligent conversations that don't just go in circles of rage, you know?

517
00:44:34,880 --> 00:44:35,980
Thank you very much.

518
00:44:35,980 --> 00:44:45,200
And also thanks a lot for showing your project to both Designing Open Democracy and this upcoming innovation Trademarked.

519
00:44:45,200 --> 00:44:46,080
So, okay, yeah.

520
00:44:46,140 --> 00:44:47,180
Thanks a lot.

521
00:44:47,180 --> 00:44:48,140
All right, great to speak.
